5. Atomic Fusion Algorithm

5.1 Multi‑Sensor Fusion Architecture

The fusion engine maintains a world model as a set of objects with state vectors and covariances. Sensors provide measurements asynchronously.

Core Loop:

```
for each sensor measurement z at time t:
    associate z with existing objects (Hungarian algorithm)
    for each matched object:
        update with Kalman filter (or extended/unscented)
    for unmatched measurements:
        initialize new object (track)
    for objects not updated:
        predict to current time
    fuse with external tracks (Link 16, etc.) using covariance intersection
```

Association Metric: Mahalanobis distance with gating.

5.2 Deep Learning for Object Detection and Classification

· Radar detections: Processed with a PointNet++ variant to classify target type (missile, aircraft, drone).
· EO/IR images: YOLOv7 with attention modules, trained on synthetic and real data.
· Acoustic signals: 1D CNN for launch detection and direction finding.

5.3 Uncertainty Estimation

Monte Carlo dropout is applied to all neural networks to obtain predictive uncertainty. High‑uncertainty tracks are flagged for human review.

